  "text": "3 Figure 15 . Schematic representation of the integrated system (MR + HT-PEMFC): two metal endplates frames (1), gold coated reformer (2), Pd-Ag membrane (3), gasket (4), MEA (5), graphite composite bipolar plate (6) and current collector [CITATION_1] . With permission of reprint of Elsevier from Ribeirinha et al. [CITATION_2] . pressure from 2 to 16 bar enhances methanol conversion more than 30%. This result points out that the role of the Pd-Ag membrane is crucial, because, by increasing the operating pressure, the hydrogen permeation driving force is intensified, determining a higher hydrogen removal with a consequent shift effect on MSR reaction toward further products formation and methanol conversion improvement. According to several literature data, it is evident that the permeation effect overcomes the thermodynamic effect, which represents the detrimental influence that is operated by higher pressures on MSR reaction, which proceeds from reaction to products with an increase of the moles number. In conclusion, among several theoretical works [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , an original modelling study was realized by Ghasemzadeh et al. [CITATION_6] , who theoretically studied MSR reaction in a silica-based MR. These authors presented both a qualitative safety and a quantitative operating analysis of a silica-based MR adoption to perform MSR reaction for hydrogen generation. The safety analysis on the system was realized by using the HAZOP method ( Figure 20) . HAZOP (Hazard and Operability) analysis was developed in the early 1970s from a tentative approach to hazard identification for process plants to an almost universally accepted approach today, and a central technique of safety engineering. More details about HAZOP analysis may be found in Taylor [CITATION_7] . In conclusion, among several theoretical works [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] , an original modelling study was realized by Ghasemzadeh et al. [CITATION_11] , who theoretically studied MSR reaction in a silica-based MR. These authors presented both a qualitative safety and a quantitative operating analysis of a silica-based MR adoption to perform MSR reaction for hydrogen generation. The safety analysis on the system was realized by using the HAZOP method ( Figure 20) . HAZOP (Hazard and Operability) analysis was developed in the early 1970s from a tentative approach to hazard identification for process plants to an almost universally accepted approach today, and a central technique of safety engineering. More details about HAZOP analysis may be found in Taylor [CITATION_12] .",
